project_announced_description: This Rural Development investment will be used to help farmers, ranchers, and rural small businesses develop renewable energy systems, and make energy efficiency improvements to their operations. Cahoys General Store LLC has been in existence since 2019 and owns and operates as a full service grocery store. Project funds will be used to make energy efficiency improvements with the purchase and installation of a six door ZeroZone cooler, nine door ZeroZone cooler, nine door ZeroZone freezer, more efficient compressor, and LED lighting. project_announced_description: This Rural Development investment will be used to build a 15,675 square foot theater in Hickman, Nebraska.The existing playhouse will be dedicated to a Youth Theater Academy and rehearsal space. The youth activities will include an educational element in the performing arts arena.The new facility will house a stage, patio, lounge, office and box office, concession area, storage area, mechanical room, lobby/waiting area, a 436-seat auditorium,a light and sound booth, storage area and a mechanical room.The new auditorium will accomplish the following goals: improve facility accessibility to those with disabilities for both increased seating capacity and other ancillary accommodations. The building increases overall seating to accommodate patron ticket demand for performances which cannot currently be met with current seating capacity. The additional seats this will also increase low-to-moderate income household utilization of the facility. And, the addition and re-purpose of the current playhouse will assist the NCP in its goal to expand the diversity of different acts that can be attracted to the facility such as musicians, bands, comedians, magicians, and dance groups.

funding_code: CF 2019 DISASTER GRANT - TORNADOES FLOODS OTHER
naics_industry_sector: Wholesale Trade (42)
project_announced_description: This Rural Development investment will be used to purchase 15 sets of bunker gear, eight self-contained breathing apparatus (SCBA) equipment with a cascade control system including the needed hoses and cylinders. The current bunker gear has reached or exceeded the 10-year lifetime standard set by the National Fire Protection Association (NFPA). The purchase of bunker gear will ensure compliance with NFPA and protects the firefighters volunteering to save lives and property. The cascade control will extend the SCBA time before the need to refill from 30 minutes to 45 minutes. Not only does it extend the time, but these will be fillable on scene, improving efficiency and time usage.The new fire equipment will keep the volunteer firefighters safe while serving to protect this community of 3,460 residents.

project_announced_description: This Rural Development investment will be used to purchase an electric cot, an updated monitor, and a defibrillator for the citys ambulance. Emergency responders are currently manually lifting and loading patients into the ambulance and operating expired health monitor and defibrillator equipment, which puts both responders and patients at risk. This new equipment will help to ensure that emergency response equipment is safe and up-to-date and provide a safer ambulance environment for all involved.

funding_code: COMMUNITY FACILITY (DIRECT AND GUARANTEED LOANS)
naics_industry_sector: Construction (23)
project_announced_description: This Rural Development investment will be used to repair several blocks of streets within the village of Unadilla. The village board has identified certain blocks where the asphalt pavement streets are in poor condition and no longer provide a functional, safe, and adequate driving surface for the traffic of Unadilla. This project will remove the existing deteriorated asphalt pavement and construct new 6-inch asphalt pavement on top of newly constructed subgrade. New curb ramps, where needed, will be constructed to satisfy Americans with Disabilities Act requirements. These new street sections will serve the village as well as some of the primary access routes to Highway 2, the Christian Church of Unadilla, local access routes, and access routes to downtown areas of Unadilla. Public safety is assured as a result of the new streets and the aforementioned curb ramps.

funding_code: (COMB LOAN & GRANT) WATER ONLY
naics_industry_sector: Utilities (22)
project_announced_description: This Rural Development investment will be used to build and improve essential water infrastructure in the Little Blue Natural Resources District. This project services 319 users in Nebraska and 54 users in Kansas. Funds will help build a new well field northeast of the village of Powell. The well site will encompass five acres and contain five wells.Backup power also willbe installed to ensure that service goes uninterrupted during an emergency. Funds also will be used to install 12.5 miles of transmission main and associated valves, fire hydrants, air releasesand modern control system. Approximately two and a half miles of redundant water main will be installed in the West system from the point of connection to improve water pressure and increase supply to this area. The existing booster pumping station will be replaced with a plant that can provide a minimum of300 gallons per minute via line that will connect to the Gladstone storage tank. Finally, the district will installnew radio read meters along with billing hard and software. This project will help to improve the quality of life for the 4,870 residents in the local service area.

naics_industry_sector: Public Administration (92)
project_announced_description: This Rural Development investment will be used to purchase two grass rig pickups, which will have specially designed work beds and other upgrades completed to outfit them with firefighting capabilities. These trucks will replace the existing grass-rig firetrucks that have reached their useful life cycles. Securing the new 4x4 pickups will greatly enhance the districts ability to respond to incidents. These cost increases are consistent with what is being seen nationwide with the effects of supply shortages and shipping costs. This project will ensure the continuity of services and will enhance public safety of the service area.

Brown County Hospital will complete a COVID-19 isolation wing in the hospital complete with a separate entrance/vestibule. The project will provide for the purchase of two generators, one for the Ainsworth Family Clinic in order to properly store vaccines and provide power backup and the second generator to service the negative pressure rooms in the hospital and maintain hospital functions in the event of a power outage. funding_code: RBCS ENTERPRISE GRANTS
naics_industry_sector: Public Administration (92)
project_announced_description: This Rural Development investment will be used to provide training and technical assistance in Fremont, NE, and Schuyler, NE for small and emerging Latino owned businesses to assist Latinos develop or start new business enterprises in their community. Workshops and trainings will be facilitated in both English and Spanish to ensure access to the information is available to the target audience. Participants will attend in-person and online workshops and panel discussions and will be provided access to business mentorship and networking. Participants will gain training, experience, and confidence in navigating the various organizations and agencies involved in funding streams, certifications, and licensure. This project is expected to assist at least 8 businesses, which will create or save 30 full-time equivalent jobs.

funding_code: RBCS ENTERPRISE NATIVE AMERICAN GRANT
naics_industry_sector: Public Administration (92)
project_announced_description: This Rural Development investment will be used to provide focused training around the use of a makerspace, related technical assistance, product and market development, to enhance individualized development of small businesses for the Santee and Omaha nations. This project will provide equipment for artisan and other businesses that would otherwise not be accessible to entrepreneurs or part-time business owners. Individual technical assistance and coaching will be provided on request to project participants. The technical assistance will provide business skills focusing on product development and marketing, which will develop new enterprises or expand existing enterprises for small businesses in the communities of Macy, Santee, and Walthill, Nebraska. This project is expected to assist a minimum of 14 small and emerging business and create or support up to 14.5 full-time equivalent jobs over the next three years.

funding_code: (COMB LOAN & GRANT) WATER ONLY
naics_industry_sector: Utilities (22)
project_announced_description: This Rural Development investment will be used to improve the water system in the citys water treatment plant required to meet applicable health and sanitary standards. The citys current system is an old iron and manganese removal plant, built in 1978, and has an aerator tower, flocculation tank, and four-cell gravity filters. The effluent is able to meet the Safe Drinking Water Act, the facility, however, is 44 years old and corrosion of the tanks (treatment vessels) for the iron and manganese are beginning to leak. The State of Nebraska is trying to increase awareness of manganese as this is considered a health hazard. The projects improvement of the water system will alleviate the problem by replacing the treatment vessels. This will deliver safe drinking water to the citys 851 residents and 479 water users.

funding_code: (LOAN ONLY) WATER ONLY
naics_industry_sector: Utilities (22)
project_announced_description: This Rural Development investment will be used to clean, paint, and upgrade features to meet current codes for their 1994 storage tank. The tank will be thoroughly cleaned prior to applying full prime epoxy & polyurethane. interior: an abrasive blast cleaning will occur prior to the application of two coats of epoxy and a finish coat. The tank will also be disinfected prior to filling. The vent will be replaced with a new state compliant 24" fail safe steel vent. The pipe rail safety climb will be replaced with an exterior galvanized safety climb system that meets current standards. An anti-climb device will be installed on the exterior ladder approximately 15ft above grade. This project will allow the village to meet current codes and extend the useful life of the tank. The Village of Wauneta has a population of 577 and median household income of $33,015.

naics_industry_sector: Health Care and Social Assistance (62)
naics_description: ASSISTED LIVING FACILITIES FOR THE ELDERLY
project_announced_description: This Rural Development investment will be used to construct 44,500 square feet including 1,500 square feet of canopy, 1,500 square feet of heated, 43,129 square feet of paving and approximately 57,500 square feet of landscaping to replace the current long-term care facility. The project includes three separate household neighborhoods. A memory care unit will include 19 beds and a separate dining area to accommodate residents in various stages of dementia and Alzheimers disease. The other two households will be designed to accommodate a blend of long-term care and short-term rehabilitation, dependent on market demand. These neighborhoods will consist of 36 private rooms and eight beds in semi-private rooms. The existing facility has far exceeded its useful life and does not meet current healthcare standards. This investment will benefit the health and safety for the residents of the service area (population 11,863, weighted median household income of $44,647) for many years to come.

naics_industry_sector: Utilities (22)
project_announced_description: This Rural Development investment will be used to improve the water system in the Village of Lodgepole. Project funds will help to make improvements to two water wells, replace deteriorating parts of the water collection system, and install transmission line and merge two wells, reducing the amount of arsenic in the water supply. The high arsenic level is a result of recent flooding and has continued to remain at an unsafe level. This project will also help to install a new 150,000-gallon water storage tank to replace the 30,000-gallon tank, which does not meet state standards for providing adequate supply amounts. The project will ensure a safe water source and promote water conservation practices.

naics_industry_sector: Utilities (22)
project_announced_description: This Rural Development investment will be used to extend service to additional users and improve service to existing users. The proposed improvement will benefit 59 residential users, 60 new residential users and 1 new other user. These improvements include the construction and installation of 34,000 linear feet of six-inch and 44,500 linear feet of four-inch water transmission mains, a new booster pump station, a new 75,000 gallon standpipe, a mobile generator, hydrants, meters, valves, fittings, and demolition of the existing standpipe and booster station. The current booster pump and standpipe is at the end of its useful life and lacks adequate capacity to serve the rural residents to be hooked up to the system. The facility will serve a population of 317 rural residents or 119 households.

project_announced_description: This Rural Development investment will be used to install Americans with Disabilities Act (ADA) bathrooms and bring a stairwell up to fire code in Preservation Madisons main facility. The building was constructed in 1913 and many areas and features do not meet the current ADA requirements. The funding request is for facility accessibility improvements that include restrooms and fire barriers throughout the building. The funding of this project will contribute to making this facility fully ADA accessible. This project will benefit more than 2,438 people, with the City of Madison.

funding_code: RBCS ENTERPRISE GRANTS
naics_industry_sector: Public Administration (92)
project_announced_description: This Rural Development investment will be used to create a permanent outdoor farmers market. The goal is to demolish two buildings that have been deemed unsafe by a structural engineer and create a permanent space for local craft and produce vendors to sell their items. The space will be enhanced with a pergola over the green space, electricity, and triangle shades over the area to protect the shoppers and vendors from the elements of the weather. The site for the outdoor market is in a prime location of downtown called Hebron and is accessible to all ages, income levels, and is easily accessed from Highway 81. By constructing a permanent space, Hebron will be able to host several community events throughout the spring, summer and fall seasons and encourage a wide variety of small businesses (e.g. food trucks, produce vendors, local crafters) across Thayer County to promote and sell goods and services within downtown Hebron. This could, in turn, increase long-term investment in Hebron downtown and generate additional sales tax for the community. The market would complement county-wide business retention by showcasing local goods and services while also encouraging job creation by providing an extra venue to host events that increase part-time and seasonal employment opportunities. This project is expected to assist at a minimum of 4 small and emerging businesses and create or support 7.5 full-time equivalent jobs in the next 3 years.

funding_code: PERSISTENT POVERTY RBCS BUSINESS ENTERPRISE NATIVE AMERICAN GRANT
naics_industry_sector: Educational Services (61)
project_announced_description: This Rural Development Investment will be used to hire an instructor for the Nebraska Indian Community Colleges Aquaculture Programs and the necessary equipment for the two next generation controlled environments agricultural, aquaponic, aquaculture and hydroponic greenhouses located on the Macy and Santee Campuses. The goal behind the program is to teach entrepreneurs how to operate a aquaculture equipment to grow food using several growing systems, and create business opportunities that collectively will foster greater food sovereignty for the Omaha Tribal communities.

funding_code: PERSISTENT POVERTY RBCS BUSINESS ENTERPRISE NATIVE AMERICAN GRANT
naics_industry_sector: Educational Services (61)
project_announced_description: This Rural Development investment will be used to supply two welding shops on the Nebraska Indian Community College campuses of Macy and Santee with the proper supplies, equipment, and a instructor. This will allow the college to offer a full welding program and complement their current construction program. Rural Development funded the construction of the welding shop with RBDG funding in 2020. Both the Omaha and Santee Reservations suffer from multiple challenges including poverty, a struggling economy, and a serious lack of economic development. Growing the vocational training opportunities at NICC via the addition of welding training will provide entrepreneurs with a useful trade skill, which is high demand in the area. This project is expected to assist at a minimum of 2 small and emerging business and will create at least 4 full-time equivalent jobs in the next three years.

funding_code: RBCS ENTERPRISE NATIVE AMERICAN GRANT
naics_industry_sector: Public Administration (92)
naics_description: AMERICAN INDIAN AND ALASKA NATIVE TRIBAL GOVERNMENTS
project_announced_description: This Rural Development investment will be used to develop a hydroponics greenhouse training center that will provide training and business opportunities to tribal members who are looking to start their own emerging businesses along with providing access to healthy food that will help decrease diet-related diseases in the Omaha tribal communities. This tribal hydroponics operation will work with the University of Nebraska-Lincoln Nation Nourishment Program that is located on the Omaha Reservation for the promotion and recruitment of emerging tribal business owners. Once the project is completed, training will include how to grow hydroponics produce, managing a hydroponics operation, starting their own hydroponics business, management their business, sales and distribution of hydroponics produce. The hydroponics greenhouse training center will also include incubator spaces for tribal members to use to start their growing operation. Produce will be sold at local farmers markets, tribally-owned grocery stores and off-reservation businesses.

funding_code: RBCS ENTERPRISE NATIVE AMERICAN GRANT
naics_industry_sector: Arts, Entertainment, and Recreation (71)
project_announced_description: This Rural Development investment will be used to assist with the interior construction of the business incubator spaces as well as space for business training and entrepreneurial development. The construction cost items include: limited interior demolition, plaster restoration, framing and gypsum board systems, a new north exit stair and deck, insulation, carpentry and casework, floor restoration, new accessible toilets, new elevator, automatic fire sprinkler system, new heating, ventilation and air conditioning, and new electrical systems including lighting, power, data and security systems installation, concrete work, plaster, flooring, painting/refinishing, exterior doors, toilet partitions/accessories, and site work. This project is expected to assist at a minimum of five small and emerging business when the completed and create or support 17.5 full-time equivalent jobs in the next three years.

funding_code: CF ARP EMERGENCY RURAL HEALTH CARE GRANTS - TRACK 1 & 2
naics_industry_sector: Health Care and Social Assistance (62)
project_announced_description: This Rural Development investment will be used to help Pender Community Health District Inc. increase telehealth capabilities. This project will help to implement an improved Electronic Health Record (EHR) system that will connect hospital patient records with clinics in Bancroft, Beemer, Emerson, and Pender. Located in a Persistent Poverty County, this project will help to provide quick and accurate access to all rural patient records in the service area of 17,730 residents.

funding_code: NATIVE AMERICAN TRIBES COMMUNITY FACILITY GRANTS
naics_industry_sector: Educational Services (61)
naics_description: ALL OTHER MISCELLANEOUS SCHOOLS AND INSTRUCTION
project_announced_description: This Rural Development investment will be used to repave a parking area and correct water drainage in Little Priest Tribal Colleges parking area to remove hazardous driving and walking conditions. The parking lot drainage has been an issue causing water to pool in areas and eroding the concrete which has created holes and areas that are hazardous to driving and walking for both students and faculty as they use the parking lot area. Replacement of the parking lot will benefit the campus, faculty and students contributing to the Native American student experience offerings by other higher education institutions for the 250 students, faculty and staff in this persistent poverty county. The community will also benefit as the parking area is used for events, farmers markets, and continuing education.

naics_industry_sector: Utilities (22)
project_announced_description: This Rural Development investment will be used to construct three miles of water main throughout the city of Neligh. The water system serves about 1,599 residents. The loan funds will be used for the construction of several water mains, miscellaneous fittings, valves, fire hydrants, and bores under existing driveways and crossing Highway 275. This work is being done to extend service to a recently annexed property, to eliminate dead-end lines (looping water mains) and to provide additional flow and fire protection areas to the City. This project will be co-funded with the Drinking Water State Revolving Loan Funds Program. The City has a MHI of $32,946.

naics_industry_sector: Public Administration (92)
project_announced_description: This Rural Development investment will be used to provide advanced, individualized small business development and training for the Santee and Omaha Nations. The project will include a collaborative makerspace with related product and market development. This makerspace will provide specific resources, technical assistance, and business coaching not otherwise accessible or affordable to artisans, entrepreneurs, or small business owners. funding_code: DISCRETION RURAL MICROPENTERPR DEV ORG
naics_industry_sector: Public Administration (92)
project_announced_description: This Rural Development investment will be used to provide business based training and technical assistance to rural microentrepreneurs and microenterprises. Center for Rural Affairs provides services in all 93 counties statewide in rural areas under 50,000 population, which includes Nebraska Congressional Districts 01-Flood, 02-Bacon and 03-Smith.

funding_code: DISCRETIONARY RMAP LOANS
naics_industry_sector: Public Administration (92)
project_announced_description: This Rural Development investment will be used to capitalize a Rural Microloan Revolving Fund to make microloans to rural microentrepreneurs and microenterprises. Funds will be used in all eligible rural areas of Nebraskas 93 counties. The Center for Rural Affairs was organized in 1973 and is a previous recipient of RMAP funding. RMAP loan funds received in Fiscal Year 2010 have provided loans to twenty-two businesses. RMAP loan funds received in Fiscal Year 2014 have provided loans to thirty businesses. RMAP loan funds received in Fiscal Year 2017 have provided loans to thirty-four businesses. This loan fund will continue to provide critical lending for Nebraskas microentrepreneurs and will help the Center for Rural Affairs Community Capital further achieve scale in Nebraska. Funding through the RMAP is making a critical difference for many startup and existing entrepreneurs in rural Nebraska.

project_announced_description: This Rural Development investment will be used to purchase a 2023 Case 321FHS high speed compact wheel payloader with a 1.7 yard bucket and pallet forks, and a 10 foot hydraulic angle snow blade. project_announced_description: This Rural Development investment will be used to replace the sewer collection system that is more than 60 years old in the Village of Taylor. The current system consists of six-inch vitrified clay pipe that has serious infiltration and inflow issues. It will be replaced with an eight-inch PVC pipe to meet current NDEE requirements and significantly reduce the existing issues, providing a long-term solution to the Village sewer problems. Village of Taylor has a population of 190 and an MHI of $31,429.

program: Meat and Poultry Processing Expansion Program
funding_code: MEAT AND POULTRY PROCESSING GRANTS - ARPA
naics_industry_sector: Manufacturing (31-33)
project_announced_description: Lot 279, LLC has been selling beef products in direct to consumer retail since 2016. In an effort to capitalize on the expanding interest in family farms building their own beef brands, Lot 279 intends to build a federally inspection portion cutting and further processing facility for use by at least three family-owned cattle producers who are seeking to create their own brands of value added beef products. The company will provide fee based processing and other services; portioning and grinding services, processing and manufacting of meats for sale to wholesale or retail customers. The facility will help ensure that small and mid sized kill facilities that are operational or being built in the region will be utilized fully.
